    <!-- ==========================================
         OUR STORY
         ========================================== -->
    <section class="section" id="our-story">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="content-width">
          <div class="section-header">
            <span class="section-label">Our Story</span>
            <h2>Where it began</h2>
          </div>

          <p class="lead">
            The Still Me Project was born from a deeply personal place &mdash; a belief that
            memory loss should never mean the loss of identity. When someone you love begins to
            forget, it can feel like the world is asking you to let go too. We started this work
            because we refused to accept that. We believed that with the right tools, the right
            support, and the right kind of attention, the essence of a person could be held,
            honored, and carried forward.
          </p>
          <p>
            What began as quiet conversations between families and caregivers has grown into
            something larger &mdash; a community of people who understand that dignity is not
            contingent on memory. We have seen what happens when someone is truly seen: the way
            a familiar song can light up a room, the way a daughter&rsquo;s voice can bring a moment
            of peace, the way a well-told story can bridge the distance that memory loss creates.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today, the Still Me Project works with families, caregivers, and communities to build
            frameworks that preserve identity and strengthen connection. We create resources that
            are warm, practical, and deeply human &mdash; because that is what this work demands.
            Every person we serve reminds us why this matters. Every story we help hold is a
            testament to the enduring power of love.
          </p>
        </div><!-- /.content-width -->
      </div><!-- /.container -->
    </section>


    <!-- ==========================================
         WHAT WE BELIEVE
         ========================================== -->
    <section class="section section--cream" id="beliefs">
      <div class="container">

        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-label">Our Values</span>
          <h2>What We Believe</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-3">

          <!-- Belief 1 -->
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-accent"></div>
            <div class="pillar-icon" aria-hidden="true">&hearts;</div>
            <h3>Every person has a story worth holding</h3>
            <p>
              No matter how memory shifts, the life someone has lived carries meaning. Their
              joys, their struggles, their humor, their love &mdash; these things do not vanish.
              They deserve to be gathered, cherished, and shared.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Belief 2 -->
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-accent"></div>
            <div class="pillar-icon" aria-hidden="true">&bull;</div>
            <h3>Connection is the foundation of care</h3>
            <p>
              The most powerful thing we can offer someone navigating memory loss is the assurance
              that they are not alone. True care lives in relationship &mdash; in the people who
              show up, listen, and stay present.
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Belief 3 -->
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-accent"></div>
            <div class="pillar-icon" aria-hidden="true">&diams;</div>
            <h3>Dignity is not a diagnosis</h3>
            <p>
              A medical diagnosis does not define a person&rsquo;s worth. Dignity belongs to every
              individual at every stage of life, and it is our responsibility to protect it with
              intention, compassion, and unwavering respect.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div><!-- /.grid-3 -->

      </div><!-- /.container -->
    </section>


